blocks.content: Define the binary topological product, which is homeomorphic to the general topological product over a two element set, but is more convenient to use. (Contributed by Jeff Madsen, 2-Sep-2009.)
blocks.origin:
axiom df-tx(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3) {
  |- wceq(ctx, cmpo(s0, s1, universe, universe, cfv(ctg, crn(cmpo(s2, s3, cv(s0), cv(s1), cxp(cv(s2), cv(s3)))))))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s3)
  -| diffss(s2, s3)
}

  ‚ä¢ tX =(s0 ‚àà ùïå, s1 ‚àà ùïå ‚Ü¶(topGen ` ran((s2 ‚àà s0, s3 ‚àà s1 ‚Ü¶(s2 √ó s3)))))
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s1)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s2)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s3)
  ‚ä£ d(s1, s2)
  ‚ä£ d(s1, s3)
  ‚ä£ d(s2, s3)
}

  -| diffss(s2, s5)

thm txval(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4) {

  -| wceq(c4, crn(cmpo(s0, s1, c0, c2, cxp(cv(s0), cv(s1)))))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s0, c2)
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c2)
} = {
  syl2an(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(c2, c3), wceq(co(c0, ctx, c2), cfv(ctg, c4)), wcel(c0, universe), wcel(c2, universe))
  elex(c0, c1)
  elex(c2, c3)
  ovmpt2a(hs0, hs1, c0, universe, c2, universe, ctx, cfv(ctg, c4), cfv(ctg, crn(cmpo(s0, s1, cv(hs0), cv(hs1), cxp(cv(s0), cv(s1))))))
  fveq2d(ctg, crn(cmpo(s0, s1, cv(hs0), cv(hs1), cxp(cv(s0), cv(s1)))), c4, wa(wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wceq(cv(hs1), c2)))
  syl6eqr(crn(cmpo(s0, s1, cv(hs0), cv(hs1), cxp(cv(s0), cv(s1)))), c4, crn(cmpo(s0, s1, c0, c2, cxp(cv(s0), cv(s1)))), wa(wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wceq(cv(hs1), c2)))
  rneqd(cmpo(s0, s1, cv(hs0), cv(hs1), cxp(cv(s0), cv(s1))), cmpo(s0, s1, c0, c2, cxp(cv(s0), cv(s1))), wa(wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wceq(cv(hs1), c2)))
  mpoeq12(s0, s1, cv(hs0), c0, cv(hs1), c2, cxp(cv(s0), cv(s1)))
  df-tx(hs0, hs1, s0, s1)
  fvex(ctg, c4)
  diff.hs0.s(hs1)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.c(universe)
  diff.hs0.c(c2)
  diff.hs0.c(cfv(ctg, c4))
  diff.hs1.c(c0)

  diff.cv.s(s1, hs0)

  diff.hs1.s(s0)
  diff.hs1.s(s1)
}

blocks.name: txbasex
blocks.content: The basis for the product topology is a set. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 2-Sep-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm txbasex(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4) {
  |- wi(wa(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(c2, c3)), wcel(c4, universe))
  -| wceq(c4, crn(cmpo(s0, s1, c0, c2, cxp(cv(s0), cv(s1)))))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s0, c2)
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c2)
} = {
  sylibr(wa(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(c2, c3)), wcel(c4, universe), wcel(cuni(c4), universe))
  syl5eqelr(cuni(c4), universe, cxp(cuni(c0), cuni(c2)), wa(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(c2, c3)))
  txuni2(s0, s1, cuni(c0), cuni(c2), c4, c0, c2)
  eqid(cuni(c0))
  eqid(cuni(c2))
  syl2an(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(c2, c3), wcel(cxp(cuni(c0), cuni(c2)), universe), wcel(cuni(c0), universe), wcel(cuni(c2), universe))

  xpexg(cuni(c0), universe, cuni(c2), universe)
  uniexb(c4)
  diff.cuni.s(s0, c0)
  diff.cuni.s(s0, c2)
  diff.cuni.s(s1, c0)
  diff.cuni.s(s1, c2)
}

blocks.name: eltx
blocks.content: A set in a product is open iff each point is surrounded by an open rectangle. (Contributed by Stefan O'Rear, 25-Jan-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm eltx(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4) {
  |- wi(wa(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(c2, c3)), wb(wcel(c4, co(c0, ctx, c2)), wral(s0, c4, wrex(s1, c0, wrex(s2, c2, wa(wcel(cv(s0), cxp(cv(s1), cv(s2))), wss(cxp(cv(s1), cv(s2)), c4)))))))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s0, c2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c4)
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c2)
  -| diffsc(s1, c4)
  -| diffsc(s2, c0)
  -| diffsc(s2, c2)
  -| diffsc(s2, c4)

blocks.name: ptbasfi
blocks.content: The basis for the product topology can also be written as the set of finite intersections of "cylinder sets", the preimages of projections into one factor from open sets in the factor. (We have to add ` X ` itself to the list because if ` A ` is empty we get ` ( fi `` (/) ) = (/) ` while ` B = { (/) } ` .) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 3-Feb-2015.)

} = {
  ptopn(s0, c0, cif(c2, cuni(cfv(c3, cv(s0))), wceq(cv(s0), c1)), c3, c4, csn(c1), w0)

  eleq2d(c2, cfv(c3, cv(s0)), cfv(c3, c1), wceq(cv(s0), c1))
  fveq2(cv(s0), c1, c3)
  adantr(wa(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c0)), wn(wceq(cv(s0), c1)), wcel(cuni(cfv(c3, cv(s0))), cfv(c3, cv(s0))))
  syl(wa(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c0)), wcel(cuni(cfv(c3, cv(s0))), cfv(c3, cv(s0))), wcel(cfv(c3, cv(s0)), ctop))
  ffvelrnda(cv(s0), c0, c3, ctop, w0)

  eqid(cuni(cfv(c3, cv(s0))))

  eldifn(cv(s0), c0, csn(c1))
  velsn(s0, c1)
  diff.csn.s(s0, c1)

blocks.name: ptclsg
blocks.content: The closure of a box in the product topology is the box formed from the closures of the factors. The proof uses the axiom of choice; the last hypothesis is the choice assumption. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 3-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: ptcls
blocks.content: The closure of a box in the product topology is the box formed from the closures of the factors. This theorem is an AC equivalent. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 2-Sep-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm ptcls(setvar s0, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wceq(cfv(cfv(ccl, c0), cixp(s0, c1, c2)), cixp(s0, c1, cfv(cfv(ccl, c3), c2))))
  -| wceq(c0, cfv(cpt, cmpt(s0, c1, c3)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c1, c4))
  -| wi(wa(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c1)), wcel(c3, cfv(ctopon, c5)))
  -| wi(wa(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c1)), wss(c2, c5))
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsw(s0, w0)
} = {
  ptclsg(s0, c0, c1, c2, c3, c4, c5, w0)
  eleqtrrd(ciun(s0, c1, c2), wacn(c1), universe, w0)
  syl2anc(w0, wcel(ciun(s0, c1, c2), universe), wcel(c1, c4), wral(s0, c1, wcel(c2, universe)))
  ralrimiva(s0, c1, w0, wcel(c2, universe))
  ssexd(c2, c5, c3, wa(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c1)))
  syl(wa(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c1)), wcel(c5, c3), wcel(c3, cfv(ctopon, c5)))
  toponmax(c3, c5)
  iunexg(s0, c1, c4, c2, universe)
  sylancr(w0, wceq(wacn(c1), universe), wac, wcel(c1, c4))
  axac3()
  acacni(c1, c4)
}

blocks.name: dfac14lem
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ dfac14 . By equipping ` S u. { P } ` for some ` P e/ S ` with the particular point topology, we can show that ` P ` is in the closure of ` S ` ; hence the sequence ` P ( x ) ` is in the product of the closures, and we can utilize this instance of ~ ptcls to extract an element of the closure of ` X_ k e. I S ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 2-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: xkoccn
blocks.content: The "constant function" function which maps ` x e. Y ` to the constant function ` z e. X |-> x ` is a continuous function from ` X ` into the space of continuous functions from ` Y ` to ` X ` . This can also be understood as the currying of the first projection function. (The currying of the second projection function is ` x e. Y |-> ( z e. X |-> z ) ` , which we already know is continuous because it is a constant function.) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 19-Mar-2015.)

blocks.name: txcnp
blocks.content: If two functions are continuous at ` D ` , then the ordered pair of them is continuous at ` D ` into the product topology. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 9-Aug-2014.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 22-Aug-2015.)

blocks.name: ptcnp
blocks.content: If every projection of a function is continuous at ` D ` , then the function itself is continuous at ` D ` into the product topology. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 3-Feb-2015.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 22-Aug-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm ptcnp(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, class c6, class c7, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wcel(cmpt(s0, c0, cmpt(s1, c1, c2)), cfv(co(c3, ccnp, c4), c5)))

blocks.name: upxp
blocks.content: Universal property of the Cartesian product considered as a categorical product in the category of sets. (Contributed by Jeff Madsen, 2-Sep-2009.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 27-Dec-2014.)

blocks.name: txcnmpt
blocks.content: A map into the product of two topological spaces is continuous if both of its projections are continuous. (Contributed by Jeff Madsen, 2-Sep-2009.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 22-Aug-2015.)

blocks.name: txcn
blocks.content: A map into the product of two topological spaces is continuous iff both of its projections are continuous. (Contributed by Jeff Madsen, 2-Sep-2009.) (Proof shortened by Mario Carneiro, 22-Aug-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm txcn(class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, class c6, class c7, class c8, class c9) {
  |- wi(w3a(wcel(c0, ctop), wcel(c1, ctop), wf(c2, c3, c4)), wb(wcel(c2, co(c5, ccn, co(c0, ctx, c1))), wa(wcel(ccom(c6, c2), co(c5, ccn, c0)), wcel(ccom(c7, c2), co(c5, ccn, c1)))))
  -| wceq(c8, cuni(c0))
  -| wceq(c9, cuni(c1))
  -| wceq(c4, cxp(c8, c9))
  -| wceq(c3, cuni(c5))
  -| wceq(c6, cres(c1st, c4))
  -| wceq(c7, cres(c2nd, c4))
} = {
  impbid(w3a(wcel(c0, ctop), wcel(c1, ctop), wf(c2, c3, c4)), wcel(c2, co(c5, ccn, co(c0, ctx, c1))), wa(wcel(ccom(c6, c2), co(c5, ccn, c0)), wcel(ccom(c7, c2), co(c5, ccn, c1))))
  3adant3(wcel(c0, ctop), wcel(c1, ctop), wf(c2, c3, c4), wi(wcel(c2, co(c5, ccn, co(c0, ctx, c1))), wa(wcel(ccom(c6, c2), co(c5, ccn, c0)), wcel(ccom(c7, c2), co(c5, ccn, c1)))))
  syl2anb(wcel(c0, ctop), wcel(c1, ctop), wi(wcel(c2, co(c5, ccn, co(c0, ctx, c1))), wa(wcel(ccom(c6, c2), co(c5, ccn, c0)), wcel(ccom(c7, c2), co(c5, ccn, c1)))), wcel(c0, cfv(ctopon, c8)), wcel(c1, cfv(ctopon, c9)))

blocks.name: ptcn
blocks.content: If every projection of a function is continuous, then the function itself is continuous into the product topology. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 3-Feb-2015.)

blocks.name: txnlly
blocks.content: If the property ` A ` is preserved under topological products, then so is the property of being n-locally ` A ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 13-Apr-2015.)
blocks.origin:

blocks.name: txtube
blocks.content: The "tube lemma". If ` X ` is compact and there is an open set ` U ` containing the line ` X X. { A } ` , then there is a "tube" ` X X. u ` for some neighborhood ` u ` of ` A ` which is entirely contained within ` U ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 21-Mar-2015.)

blocks.name: hausdiag
blocks.content: A topology is Hausdorff iff the diagonal set is closed in the topology's product with itself. _EDITORIAL_: very clumsy proof, can probably be shortened substantially. (Contributed by Stefan O'Rear, 25-Jan-2015.) (Proof shortened by Peter Mazsa, 2-Oct-2022.)

blocks.name: hauseqlcld
blocks.content: In a Hausdorff topology, the equalizer of two continuous functions is closed (thus, two continuous functions which agree on a dense set agree everywhere). (Contributed by Stefan O'Rear, 25-Jan-2015.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 22-Aug-2015.)

blocks.name: txkgen
blocks.content: The topological product of a locally compact space and a compactly generated Hausdorff space is compactly generated. (The condition on ` S ` can also be replaced with either "compactly generated weak Hausdorff (CGWH)" or "compact Hausdorff-ly generated (CHG)", where WH means that all images of compact Hausdorff spaces are closed and CHG means that a set is open iff it is open in all compact Hausdorff spaces.) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 23-Mar-2015.)

blocks.name: xkohaus
blocks.content: If the codomain space is Hausdorff, then the compact-open topology of continuous functions is also Hausdorff. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 19-Mar-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm xkohaus(class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(wa(wcel(c0, ctop), wcel(c1, cha)), wcel(co(c1, cxko, c0), cha))
} = {
  sylanbrc(wa(wcel(c0, ctop), wcel(c1, cha)), wcel(co(c1, cxko, c0), cha), wcel(co(c1, cxko, c0), ctop), wral(hs0, cuni(co(c1, cxko, c0)), wral(hs1, cuni(co(c1, cxko, c0)), wi(wne(cv(hs0), cv(hs1)), wrex(hs2, co(c1, cxko, c0), wrex(hs3, co(c1, cxko, c0), w3a(wcel(cv(hs0), cv(hs2)), wcel(cv(hs1), cv(hs3)), wceq(cin(cv(hs2), cv(hs3)), emptycls))))))))

blocks.name: xkoco1cn
blocks.content: If ` F ` is a continuous function, then ` g |-> g o. F ` is a continuous function on function spaces. (The reason we prove this and ~ xkoco2cn independently of the more general ~ xkococn is because that requires some inconvenient extra assumptions on ` S ` .) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 20-Mar-2015.)
